(viii)  organize a regional workshop on community participation in developing carbon 
financing  opportunities  through  more  sustainable  grassland  management  in 
Northeast Asia; 
(ix)  prepare a final report on approaches to community participation in voluntary 
carbon markets through more sustainable grassland management in Northeast 
Asia (to be published as ADB knowledge product by month 22); 
(x)  provide training to government counterpart staff; and 
(xi)  participate in regional workshops and conferences.  

5.  Climate  change  specialist  and  national  coordinator  (national,  2  consultants,  16 
person-months each). The specialist will have a good command of the English language and 
have  at  least  10  years  of  professional  experience  in  international  donor-funded  projects, 
including project management. The specialist will be responsible for coordinating the work of the 
national team. The specialist will 

(i)  act as main liaison between the international consultants team, the government 
implementing agency, the national technical working group, and ADB; 
(ii)  manage and ensure the timely implementation of the TA at the national level; 
(iii)  act as the secretary of the national technical working group; 
(iv)  coordinate the preparation and completion of the national studies and reports; 
(v)  contribute to the preparation and completion of the TA inception, midterm, and 
final reports; 
(vi)  contribute  to  the  assessment  of  the  economic  valuation  of  the  grasslands  in 
Northeast Asia; 
(vii)  contribute to the assessment of opportunities for carbon financing of grassland 
sequestration; 
(viii)  establish cooperation mechanisms to supplement ongoing regional and national 
initiatives for soil carbon and land degradation monitoring;  
(ix)  contribute to the preparation of the report on potential financing mechanisms for 
sustainable grassland management; 
(x)  contribute to the preparation of national project proposals for potential carbon 
financing; 
(xi)  provide inputs for the final recommendations on opportunities to access carbon 
markets,  including  possible  changes  needed  in  the  regulatory  and  policy 
framework; 
(xii)  participate in and present relevant topics at project seminars and workshops; and 
(xiii)  prepare the report on potential financing mechanisms for sustainable grassland 
management. 

6.  Grassland monitoring specialist (national, 2 consultants, 8 person-months each). The 
specialist will support the international soil specialist. The specialist will have a good command 
of the English language and have at least 8 years of professional experience, preferably also in 
international donor-funded projects. The specialist will  

(i)  collect  data  and  review  the  national  policy  and  regulatory  framework  for 
grassland management; 
(ii)  collect data on the link between conditions of grasslands and occurrence of dust 
and sandstorms; 
(iii)  review regional data monitoring and information-sharing arrangements regarding 
land degradation and carbon stocks;  
(iv)  help design a soil carbon monitoring network at the demonstration sites;

